english:
  title: Three Poems on the Cold Wind, Composed Together with Yeop Gong-so
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I.

    The cold wind blows from northwest,
    and the wanderer yearns for home.
    Sorrow settles through the long night—
    lamplights flicker across my bed.
    The ancient road grows ever distant;
    I can only watch the clouds drift by.
    Alas, the pine trees in the garden
    deepen their green with the year's decline.
    Let us cherish the bonds of friendship
    and preserve our hearts like jade and gold.

    II.

    The cold wind blows from northwest,
    blowing both day and night without rest.
    Clouds scatter across the azure expanse,
    and through the trees comes a rushing sound.
    At dawn, official duties call;
    I ride forth in heavy furs, whipping my horse.
    The warriors shout upon the roads,
    while a hundred worries burn in my heart.
    What use to wait until the sun climbs three times high,
    then slowly rise with uncombed hair?

    III.

    The cold wind blows from northwest;
    thick shadows gradually gather and bind.
    Sitting still, I hear the wind's strength rise—
    soon, it seems, the snow will fall.
    In an instant, ten thousand cranes dance,
    transformations fleeting as an eyeblink.
    Behind closed doors I hum alone,
    while on the road a cart axle breaks.
    When the ancient qin sounds in my ears
    and incense burns, its clarity is boundless.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem is composed as three separate pieces on the same theme, a common poetic form in classical East Asian poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'jade and gold' (금옥) is a classical metaphor for moral character and integrity.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'cranes' (학) in the third poem symbolize longevity and immortality in East Asian poetic tradition.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'ancient qin' (초석금) refers to a traditional stringed instrument; its sound represents refined solitude and contemplation.
